      <div class="fg-stepgrid">
        <div class="fg-step"><b>1</b><span><strong>Pick a grid</strong> — 32×32 is the sweet spot. Or import a GIF and remix it (<em>the</em> banana is one click away).</span></div>
        <div class="fg-step"><b>2</b><span><strong>Draw</strong> — pencil, fill, eraser. Watch the live chat preview while you work.</span></div>
        <div class="fg-step"><b>3</b><span><strong>Animate</strong> — add frames, duplicate, nudge. Onion skin ghosts the previous one.</span></div>
        <div class="fg-step"><b>4</b><span><strong>Forge it</strong> — transparent GIF or PNG, ready to upload to Discord, Twitch or Slack.</span></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="fg-drawgif">
      <h2>Draw an animated GIF from scratch</h2>
      <p>
        Every big GIF maker converts video. The Forge is the other kind — a
        <strong>GIF drawing tool</strong>, like the ones the first GIF artists used. Draw each
        frame in pixels, set the timing, export a real animated GIF with real transparency.
        Nothing converted, everything <em>drawn</em>. If you can doodle, you can animate.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="fg-facts" aria-label="Pixel facts">
      <div class="fg-fact"><b>1989</b> GIFs learn to animate and go transparent (GIF89a) — your emotes ship in that same format</div>
      <div class="fg-fact"><b>28 px</b> the size a Twitch emote actually renders in chat — draw for it, don't shrink to it</div>
      <div class="fg-fact"><b>1999</b> the dancing banana is drawn in a tool this simple — 27 years later it's still everywhere</div>
      <div class="fg-fact"><b>256</b> colours per GIF frame, plus one transparent — constraints are where style comes from</div>
    </section>

